{"title":"ERG mode explained: what is it, how to use it and when you should turn it off","link":"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/erg-mode/","date":1613073630000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><section itemprop=\"articleBody\"><p>Sales of <a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/fitness-and-training/which-indoor-training-solution-is-best-for-you/\">indoor trainers</a> have exploded, with major bike retailers reporting sales increases of between 500 and 1,000 per cent in the UK in 2020.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.bikeradar.com/advice/buyers-guides/best-smart-trainer/\">Smart trainers</a> account for a large proportion of these sales, where “smart” refers to the ability of a computer program or app to talk to the trainer and control the bike’s resistance without the need for a rider to shift gears.</p><p>One notable feature of smart trainers is the ability to ride a workout in ‘ERG mode’, so let’s take a look at exactly what ERG mode is, why and when you might want to use it, as well as the key advantages and disadvantages it can offer.</p><h2>What is ERG mode?</h2><div><picture><source media=\"(max-width: 320px)\" data-srcset=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/02/20191018_SB_5DSR_MG_8246-b6b675a.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=90&amp;resize=299%2C199, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/02/20191018_SB_5DSR_MG_8246-b6b675a.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=599%2C399 2x, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/02/20191018_SB_5DSR_MG_8246-b6b675a.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=899%2C599 3x, https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/02/20191018_SB_5DSR_MG_8246-b6b675a.jpg?webp=true&amp;quality=45&amp;resize=1199%2C799 4x\" type=\"image/webp\"><source media=\"(max-width: 320px)\" data-srcset=\"https://images.immediate.co.uk/production/volatile/sites/21/2019/02/20191018_SB_5DSR_MG_8246-b6b675a.jpg?quality=90